                <h3><ins>WHAT IS DRUG ABUSE ?</ins></h3><br>
                <p>Drug abuse refers to the intentional misuse of drugs, whether prescription or illegal, for non-medical purposes. 
                   It involves using drugs in a way that is harmful to physical and mental health, and may also have negative social and economic consequences.
                </p><br>
                <h3>WHY DRUGS ARE ADDICTIVE ?</h3><br>
                <p>Drugs can be addictive because they affect the reward system in the brain. When a person takes drugs, the brain releases a surge of dopamine, a neurotransmitter that is associated with pleasure and reward. This dopamine release creates a sense of euphoria or intense pleasure, which can reinforce drug use and encourage the person to repeat the behavior.

                    Over time, drug use can change the brain's chemistry and structure, leading to physical and psychological dependence on the drug.<br> As the brain becomes accustomed to the presence of the drug, it may stop producing dopamine in response to natural rewards such as food, sex, or social interaction, leading to a reduced ability to experience pleasure from these normal activities. This can make the drug use seem more appealing and necessary, further reinforcing the cycle of addiction.
                    
                    Different drugs can have different addictive properties, and some people may be more vulnerable to addiction than others due to genetic, environmental, or psychological factors. Addiction is a complex and multi-dimensional phenomenon, and successful treatment often involves a combination of behavioral therapy, medication, and support from family and community.
                </p><br>
