                <h3>HOW DRUGS AFFECT THE YOUNGSTER'S ?</h3><br>
                <p>Drug use can have serious consequences for young people, both in the short-term and long-term. Here are some ways that drugs can affect youngsters:</p><br>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p><b>Impaired brain development:</b> The brain continues to develop throughout adolescence and into early adulthood. Drug use during this critical period can interfere with normal brain development, leading to long-lasting changes in brain function and structure.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <b>Increased risk of addiction:</b> Young people who use drugs are more likely to develop addiction later in life. The earlier drug use begins, the higher the risk of addiction.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <b>Poor academic performance:</b> Drug use can interfere with academic performance, leading to poor grades, absenteeism, and even dropping out of school.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <b>Social and emotional problems:</b> Drug use can lead to social isolation, conflict with family and friends, and emotional problems such as depression and anxiety.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <b>Increased risk of injury and death:</b> Drug use can impair judgment, coordination, and reaction time, increasing the risk of accidents, injuries, and even death.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
